1
00:00:13,263 --> 00:00:15,807
There we go. Perfect landing.

2
00:00:15,933 --> 00:00:17,976
Which isn't easy in such a tight spot.

3
00:00:18,060 --> 00:00:20,312
You should be used to tight spots
by now.

4
00:00:21,355 --> 00:00:24,149
-Where are we?
-The end of the line.

5
00:00:27,569 --> 00:00:29,821
No place like it.

6
00:00:36,787 --> 00:00:38,372
Home?

7
00:00:38,455 --> 00:00:40,999
-You took me home?
-Back to the morning after we left.

8
00:00:41,124 --> 00:00:43,877
So you've only been gone
about 12 hours. No time at all, really.

9
00:00:43,961 --> 00:00:47,923
But all the stuff we've done,
Shakespeare, New New York, old New York.

10
00:00:48,048 --> 00:00:50,175
Yep. All in one night.

11
00:00:50,259 --> 00:00:52,594
Relatively speaking,
everything should be just as it was.

12
00:00:52,678 --> 00:00:55,973
Books, CDs, laundry.

13
00:00:57,391 --> 00:01:00,227
So, back where you were, as promised.

14
00:01:01,562 --> 00:01:05,232
-This is it?
-Yeah, I should probably...

15
00:01:05,315 --> 00:01:06,900
(PHONE RINGING)

16
00:01:06,984 --> 00:01:08,735
MARTHA: Hi, I'm out. Leave a message.

17
00:01:08,819 --> 00:01:10,862
I'm sorry.

18
00:01:10,946 --> 00:01:13,615
WOMAN: Martha, are you there?
Pick it up, will you?

19
00:01:13,699 --> 00:01:15,492
It's Mum. It'll wait.

20
00:01:15,576 --> 00:01:18,328
All right, then.
Pretend that you're out if you like.

21
00:01:18,495 --> 00:01:21,373
I was only calling to say
that your sister's on TV.

22
00:01:21,456 --> 00:01:25,210
On the news of all things.
Just thought you might be interested.

23
00:01:25,294 --> 00:01:28,422
-The details are top secret...
-How could Tish end up on the news?

24
00:01:28,505 --> 00:01:30,340
...but I can tell you that tonight,

25
00:01:30,424 --> 00:01:32,509
I will demonstrate a device
which will...

26
00:01:32,593 --> 00:01:35,304
She got a new job
doing PR for some research lab.

27
00:01:35,387 --> 00:01:38,765
With the push of a single button,

28
00:01:38,849 --> 00:01:42,894
I will change what it means to be human.

29
00:01:43,395 --> 00:01:45,564
REPORTER: Professor! Professor!

30
00:01:45,647 --> 00:01:48,358
Sorry. You were saying you should...

31
00:01:49,568 --> 00:01:52,029
Yes, yes. I should.

32
00:01:53,739 --> 00:01:57,326
-One trip we said.
-Yeah.

33
00:01:57,951 --> 00:02:00,829
I suppose things just kind of escalated.

34
00:02:00,912 --> 00:02:03,915
Mmm. Seems to happen to me a lot.

35
00:02:06,376 --> 00:02:09,421
Thank you. For everything.

36
00:02:10,589 --> 00:02:12,883
It was my pleasure.

37
00:02:22,142 --> 00:02:24,144
(WHOOSHING)

38
00:02:39,326 --> 00:02:41,912
(WHOOSHING)

39
00:02:50,045 --> 00:02:54,424
No, I'm sorry. Did he say he was going
to change what it means to be human?

40
00:02:54,758 --> 00:02:57,094
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

41
00:03:32,546 --> 00:03:34,297
Are you sure it's safe?

42
00:03:34,381 --> 00:03:37,300
There were some issues.
They've been resolved.

43
00:03:37,384 --> 00:03:40,262
I'm confident I'm in no serious danger.

44
00:03:40,345 --> 00:03:44,349
That's comforting, Richard, but it
wasn't just you I was worried about.

45
00:03:44,474 --> 00:03:45,892
Your concern is touching.

46
00:03:45,976 --> 00:03:48,061
The people in that room will represent

47
00:03:48,145 --> 00:03:50,731
billions of pounds worth
of potential investment.

48
00:03:51,314 --> 00:03:54,526
Mr Saxon wants to be sure
they like what they see.

49
00:03:56,027 --> 00:03:59,656
Don't worry.
Our friend will get his money's worth.

50
00:04:02,701 --> 00:04:05,662
You wanted to see the guest list
for tonight, Professor?

51
00:04:05,746 --> 00:04:07,789
Yes, thank you, Letitia.

52
00:04:11,376 --> 00:04:12,878
(SNIFFING)

53
00:04:13,003 --> 00:04:15,797
That's an interesting perfume.
What's it called?

54
00:04:16,882 --> 00:04:18,550
Soap.

55
00:04:24,389 --> 00:04:26,183
Oh, black tie.

56
00:04:26,266 --> 00:04:28,477
Whenever I wear this,
something bad always happens.

57
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:31,229
It's not the outfit, that's just you.

58
00:04:31,313 --> 00:04:35,442
Anyway, I think it suits you
in a James Bond kind of way.

59
00:04:35,525 --> 00:04:39,029
James Bond? Really?

60
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:04,346
Oh, look, they've got nibbles!
I love nibbles.

61
00:05:07,474 --> 00:05:10,393
-Hello!
-Tish!

62
00:05:11,102 --> 00:05:13,396
You look great.

63
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:15,398
So, what do you think?
Impressive, isn't it?

64
00:05:15,565 --> 00:05:17,567
-Very.
-And two nights out in a row for you.

65
00:05:17,651 --> 00:05:19,486
That's dangerously close
to a social life.

66
00:05:19,569 --> 00:05:21,488
If I keep this up,
I'll end up in all the gossip columns.

67
00:05:21,571 --> 00:05:24,491
You might, actually. You should keep
an eye out for photographers. And Mum.

68
00:05:24,574 --> 00:05:27,077
She's coming, too.
Even dragging Leo along with her.

69
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:30,622
Leo? In black tie? That I must see.

70
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:34,334
-This is the Doctor.
-Hello.

71
00:05:35,919 --> 00:05:38,088
-Is he with you?
-Yeah.

72
00:05:38,213 --> 00:05:40,423
But he's not on the list.
How did he get in?

73
00:05:40,507 --> 00:05:42,050
He's my plus one.

74
00:05:42,133 --> 00:05:44,094
So this Lazarus, he's your boss?

75
00:05:44,177 --> 00:05:47,013
Professor Lazarus, yes.
I'm part of his executive staff.

76
00:05:47,097 --> 00:05:48,932
She's in the PR department.

77
00:05:49,015 --> 00:05:51,101
I'm head of the PR department, actually.

78
00:05:51,226 --> 00:05:53,395
-You're joking!
-I put this whole thing together.

79
00:05:53,478 --> 00:05:55,772
So do you know what the Professor's
going to be doing tonight?

80
00:05:55,856 --> 00:05:59,025
That looks like it might be
a sonic micro-field manipulator.

81
00:05:59,109 --> 00:06:01,611
He's a science geek. I should've known.

82
00:06:01,695 --> 00:06:05,657
Got to get back to work now.
I'll catch up with you later.

83
00:06:05,740 --> 00:06:07,450
Science geek? What's that mean?

84
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:10,453
That you're obsessively
enthusiastic about it.

85
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:12,038
Oh. Nice.

86
00:06:12,122 --> 00:06:15,750
Your father's caused me enough
heartache already with his menopause

87
00:06:15,834 --> 00:06:18,628
-and his trophy girlfriend.
-Yeah, Mum, I know.

88
00:06:18,712 --> 00:06:20,755
It was just something
he said last night.

89
00:06:20,839 --> 00:06:23,300
-Martha.
-Mum.

90
00:06:24,342 --> 00:06:25,927
Oh.

91
00:06:26,011 --> 00:06:28,638
All right, what's the occasion?

92
00:06:28,722 --> 00:06:31,516
What do you mean?
I'm just pleased to see you, that's all.

93
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:36,438
-But you saw me last night.
-I know, I just missed you.

94
00:06:37,272 --> 00:06:38,732
You're looking good, Leo.

95
00:06:38,815 --> 00:06:41,860
Yeah, if anyone asks me to fetch them
a drink, I'll swing for them.

96
00:06:41,985 --> 00:06:44,905
-You disappeared last night.
-I...

97
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:48,241
-...just went home.
-On your own?

98
00:06:50,493 --> 00:06:52,829
This is a friend of mine, the Doctor.

99
00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:55,749
-Doctor what?
-No, it's just the Doctor.

100
00:06:55,832 --> 00:06:57,918
-We've been doing some work together.
-All right.

101
00:06:58,001 --> 00:07:00,337
Lovely to meet you, Mrs Jones.
Heard a lot about you.

102
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:02,714
Have you? What've you heard, then?

103
00:07:02,797 --> 00:07:06,134
Well, you know,
that you're Martha's mother and...

104
00:07:08,136 --> 00:07:09,679
Um...

105
00:07:10,347 --> 00:07:13,058
No, actually, that's about it.
We haven't had much time to chat.

106
00:07:13,141 --> 00:07:17,646
-You know, been busy.
-Busy? Doing what exactly?

107
00:07:17,729 --> 00:07:21,358
Oh. You know. Stuff.

108
00:07:24,027 --> 00:07:28,448
Ladies and gentlemen,
I am Professor Richard Lazarus,

109
00:07:28,531 --> 00:07:31,868
and tonight I'm going
to perform a miracle.

110
00:07:33,036 --> 00:07:36,373
It is, I believe,
the most important advance

111
00:07:36,456 --> 00:07:39,250
since Rutherford split the atom.

112
00:07:39,334 --> 00:07:43,463
The biggest leap
since Armstrong stood on the moon.

113
00:07:44,464 --> 00:07:47,926
Tonight you will watch and wonder.

114
00:07:49,052 --> 00:07:54,474
But tomorrow, you will wake to a world
which will be changed forever.

115
00:08:14,953 --> 00:08:16,788
(DEVICE SCREECHING)

116
00:08:34,681 --> 00:08:36,641
(ALARM BLARING)

117
00:08:36,766 --> 00:08:38,643
Something's wrong. It's overloading.

118
00:08:53,742 --> 00:08:56,953
Somebody stop him!
Get him away from those controls!

119
00:08:57,120 --> 00:09:01,332
If this goes up, it'll take the whole
building with it! Is that what you want?

120
00:09:13,470 --> 00:09:15,638
DOCTOR: Get it open.

121
00:09:41,331 --> 00:09:43,166
Ladies and gentlemen.

122
00:09:44,167 --> 00:09:46,169
I am Richard Lazarus.

123
00:09:47,212 --> 00:09:49,339
I am 76 years old

124
00:09:50,215 --> 00:09:52,258
and I am reborn!

125
00:09:57,013 --> 00:10:00,934
He did it. He actually did it!

126
00:10:04,854 --> 00:10:08,775
That can't be the same guy.
It's impossible. It must be a trick.

127
00:10:08,858 --> 00:10:11,694
Oh, it's not a trick. I wish it were.

128
00:10:12,445 --> 00:10:15,031
What just happened, then?

129
00:10:15,115 --> 00:10:18,034
He just changed what it means
to be human.

130
00:10:20,537 --> 00:10:22,372
Excuse me.

131
00:10:23,998 --> 00:10:28,044
That was the most astonishing thing
I've ever seen.

132
00:10:29,546 --> 00:10:33,133
-Look at you!
-This is only the beginning.

133
00:10:33,216 --> 00:10:37,011
We're not just making history,
we're shaping the future, too.

134
00:10:37,095 --> 00:10:39,389
Think of the money we'll make.

135
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:43,393
People will sell their souls
to be transformed like that.

136
00:10:43,893 --> 00:10:46,521
And I'll be first in line.

137
00:11:00,410 --> 00:11:02,662
-Richard!
-I'm famished.

138
00:11:03,621 --> 00:11:07,417
Energy deficit. Always happens
with this kind of process.

139
00:11:07,542 --> 00:11:09,627
You talk as if
you see this every day, Mr...?

140
00:11:09,711 --> 00:11:13,381
Doctor. And, well, no, not every day,
but I have some experience

141
00:11:13,464 --> 00:11:16,009
-with this kind of transformation.
-That's not possible.

142
00:11:16,092 --> 00:11:18,678
Using hypersonic sound waves
to create a state of resonance,

143
00:11:18,761 --> 00:11:21,723
-that's inspired.
-You understand the theory, then?

144
00:11:21,806 --> 00:11:23,641
Enough to know that
you couldn't possibly

145
00:11:23,766 --> 00:11:25,727
have allowed for all the variables.

146
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:30,023
-No experiment is entirely without risk.
-That thing nearly exploded.

147
00:11:30,106 --> 00:11:32,066
You might as well
have stepped into a blender.

148
00:11:32,150 --> 00:11:34,527
You're not qualified to comment.

149
00:11:34,611 --> 00:11:36,362
If I hadn't stopped it,
it would've exploded.

150
00:11:36,446 --> 00:11:40,325
Then I thank you, Doctor.
But that's a simple engineering issue.

151
00:11:40,450 --> 00:11:43,494
What happened inside the capsule
was exactly what was supposed to happen.

152
00:11:43,620 --> 00:11:45,121
No more, no less.

153
00:11:45,246 --> 00:11:48,374
You've no way of knowing that
until you've run proper tests.

154
00:11:48,458 --> 00:11:52,712
Look at me! You can see what happened.
I'm all the proof you need.

155
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:56,883
The device will be properly certified
before we start to operate commercially.

156
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:00,261
Commercially? You are joking?
That'll cause chaos.

157
00:12:00,386 --> 00:12:03,723
Not chaos, change.

158
00:12:03,806 --> 00:12:06,643
A chance for humanity
to evolve, to improve.

159
00:12:06,726 --> 00:12:08,394
This isn't about improving,

160
00:12:08,478 --> 00:12:11,314
this is about you and your customers
living a little longer.

161
00:12:11,397 --> 00:12:15,276
Not a little longer, Doctor,
a lot longer.

162
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:16,819
Perhaps indefinitely.

163
00:12:16,945 --> 00:12:21,449
Richard, we have things to discuss.
Upstairs.

164
00:12:21,574 --> 00:12:23,743
Goodbye, Doctor.

165
00:12:23,826 --> 00:12:27,747
In a few years, you'll look back
and laugh at how wrong you were.

166
00:12:34,003 --> 00:12:36,589
Oh, he's out of his depth.

167
00:12:36,673 --> 00:12:38,800
He's no idea the damage
he might've done.

168
00:12:38,883 --> 00:12:42,178
-So what do we do now?
-Now...

169
00:12:43,096 --> 00:12:47,100
Well, this building must be full of
laboratories. I say we do our own tests.

170
00:12:47,183 --> 00:12:50,353
Lucky I've just collected
a DNA sample then, isn't it?

171
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:54,357
Oh, Martha Jones, you're a star!

172
00:12:57,026 --> 00:13:01,197
I grew up over there.
Tiny flat above a butcher's shop.

173
00:13:02,031 --> 00:13:04,242
It'll have a blue plaque soon.

174
00:13:04,367 --> 00:13:07,537
-"Richard Lazarus lived here."
-It's gone.

175
00:13:08,746 --> 00:13:13,084
-Destroyed in the war. The bombing.
-Of course.

176
00:13:14,043 --> 00:13:16,129
1940. Do you remember?

177
00:13:16,879 --> 00:13:20,341
Night after night. Explosions.

178
00:13:22,051 --> 00:13:25,263
Guns. Firestorms.

179
00:13:25,388 --> 00:13:28,725
My parents had sent me
to the country by then.

180
00:13:28,808 --> 00:13:32,353
When the sirens went,
we'd go to the cathedral there.

181
00:13:32,478 --> 00:13:34,897
We used to shelter in the crypt.

182
00:13:35,606 --> 00:13:38,568
The living cowering among the dead.

183
00:13:38,651 --> 00:13:41,904
But look what you've built here now.

184
00:13:41,988 --> 00:13:45,074
You've laid the foundations
for an empire.

185
00:13:45,908 --> 00:13:49,078
An empire we can rule together.

186
00:13:57,003 --> 00:13:58,504
What's wrong?

187
00:14:05,053 --> 00:14:07,096
Look at yourself, woman.

188
00:14:11,559 --> 00:14:13,853
-Amazing.
-What?

189
00:14:13,978 --> 00:14:17,357
-Lazarus' DNA.
-I can't see anything different.

190
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:19,942
-Look at it.
-Oh, my God!

191
00:14:20,068 --> 00:14:21,903
Did that just change?

192
00:14:22,737 --> 00:14:25,365
-But it can't have.
-But it did.

193
00:14:25,448 --> 00:14:26,741
It's impossible.

194
00:14:26,824 --> 00:14:29,535
And that's two impossible things
we've seen so far tonight.

195
00:14:29,619 --> 00:14:31,537
Don't you love it when that happens?

196
00:14:31,621 --> 00:14:34,957
That means Lazarus has changed
his own molecular patterns.

197
00:14:35,041 --> 00:14:37,293
Hypersonic sound waves
to destabilise the cell structure.

198
00:14:37,377 --> 00:14:40,213
Then a metagenic program to manipulate
the coding in the protein strands.

199
00:14:40,296 --> 00:14:44,384
Basically, he hacked into his own
genes and instructed them to rejuvenate.

200
00:14:44,467 --> 00:14:48,388
-But they're still mutating now.
-Because he missed something.

201
00:14:48,471 --> 00:14:52,141
Something in his DNA that's been
activated and won't let him stabilise.

202
00:14:52,266 --> 00:14:54,060
Something that's trying to change him.

203
00:14:54,143 --> 00:14:56,562
-Change him into what?
-I don't know.

204
00:14:56,646 --> 00:14:58,815
But I think we need to find out.

205
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:00,775
That woman said
they were going upstairs.

206
00:15:00,858 --> 00:15:02,318
Let's go.

207
00:15:02,985 --> 00:15:05,696
It's me who made all this possible.

208
00:15:05,822 --> 00:15:08,950
This is my triumph
and I will not be denied.

209
00:15:09,033 --> 00:15:11,077
Not by you.
Not after everything I've done.

210
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:12,245
(SCOFFS)

211
00:15:12,328 --> 00:15:15,915
You backed me because you saw profit.
Your concern was financial.

212
00:15:15,998 --> 00:15:18,543
You want the money as much as I do.

213
00:15:19,335 --> 00:15:21,462
We had a plan.

214
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:24,924
When the device is ready,
I'll be rejuvenated, too.

215
00:15:25,007 --> 00:15:28,344
We could be rich and young and together.

216
00:15:29,387 --> 00:15:32,390
You think I'd waste another lifetime
on you?

217
00:15:34,851 --> 00:15:38,312
Did that process make you
even more cruel?

218
00:15:39,188 --> 00:15:44,110
No, my love, that I learned from you.
You have a gift for it.

219
00:15:44,193 --> 00:15:48,281
Then you'll know that I'll protect
my involvement in the project.

220
00:15:48,364 --> 00:15:50,908
I'm sure Mr Saxon will be interested...

221
00:15:52,368 --> 00:15:54,537
What's going on?

222
00:15:55,455 --> 00:15:57,874
It must just be...

223
00:15:57,957 --> 00:15:59,834
What is it?

224
00:16:00,793 --> 00:16:04,213
I'll be fine in a moment.
It's probably just cramp.

225
00:16:07,717 --> 00:16:09,385
Richard?

226
00:16:11,471 --> 00:16:14,098
Is it some kind of seizure?

227
00:16:14,223 --> 00:16:18,728
What should I do?
I don't understand. What's happening?

228
00:16:19,729 --> 00:16:21,147
Richard?

229
00:16:22,398 --> 00:16:24,525
(GROWLING)

230
00:16:36,245 --> 00:16:40,750
Tish, have you seen Martha
and that Doctor anywhere?

231
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:42,335
Not since the demonstration.

232
00:16:42,418 --> 00:16:44,879
Do you know anything about him?
Has she ever mentioned him before?

233
00:16:44,962 --> 00:16:46,923
-Not to me.
-The way she followed him...

234
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,175
She's a doctor.
She was just doing her job.

235
00:16:49,258 --> 00:16:53,095
She's not a doctor yet. Never will be
if she doesn't stay focussed.

236
00:16:53,221 --> 00:16:55,723
Look, she's found a bloke. So what?

237
00:16:55,806 --> 00:17:00,269
There's something's going on, Leo.
I can feel it.

238
00:17:17,036 --> 00:17:21,832
Letitia Jones. I'd recognise
the smell of that soap anywhere.

239
00:17:21,958 --> 00:17:23,417
Professor.

240
00:17:23,501 --> 00:17:25,628
I'm sorry, ladies and gentlemen.
You'll have to excuse me

241
00:17:25,753 --> 00:17:29,632
while I take care of Letitia here.
I've been neglecting her.

242
00:17:37,807 --> 00:17:42,144
-This is his office all right.
-So where is he?

243
00:17:42,979 --> 00:17:47,233
Don't know.
Let's try back at the...reception.

244
00:17:55,783 --> 00:17:59,161
-Is that Lady Thaw?
-Used to be.

245
00:17:59,829 --> 00:18:03,833
It's just a shell, had all
the life-energy drained out of her.

246
00:18:04,959 --> 00:18:07,962
Like squeezing the juice
out of an orange.

247
00:18:08,045 --> 00:18:10,214
-Lazarus!
-Could be.

248
00:18:10,298 --> 00:18:13,384
-So he's changed already.
-Not necessarily.

249
00:18:13,509 --> 00:18:16,470
You saw the DNA, it was fluctuating.
The process must demand energy.

250
00:18:16,554 --> 00:18:19,473
-This might not have been enough.
-So he might do this again?

251
00:18:19,557 --> 00:18:20,933
Mmm.

252
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:27,815
(TISH LAUGHING)

253
00:18:27,898 --> 00:18:30,901
You seem very young to have
such a responsible position.

254
00:18:31,027 --> 00:18:33,946
-Have you much experience?
-Not really.

255
00:18:34,030 --> 00:18:36,616
But the interview panel thought
I had all the necessary attributes.

256
00:18:36,699 --> 00:18:38,743
How perceptive of them.

257
00:18:40,077 --> 00:18:41,954
So, where are you taking me?

258
00:18:42,038 --> 00:18:45,082
Up to the roof. It's a lovely evening.
I thought I'd show you the view.

259
00:18:45,166 --> 00:18:49,086
-It's extraordinary.
-Like a lot of things round here, then.

260
00:18:59,221 --> 00:19:02,058
-I can't see him.
-He can't be far. Keep looking.

261
00:19:02,141 --> 00:19:04,352
You all right, Marth?
I think Mum wants to talk to you.

262
00:19:04,435 --> 00:19:06,103
Have you seen Lazarus anywhere?

263
00:19:06,228 --> 00:19:08,147
He was getting cosy
with Tish a couple of minutes ago.

264
00:19:08,230 --> 00:19:09,899
-With Tish?
-Ah, Doctor.

265
00:19:10,024 --> 00:19:12,652
-Where did they go?
-Upstairs, I think. Why?

266
00:19:12,735 --> 00:19:16,364
-Doctor... I'm speaking to you!
-Not now, Mum!

267
00:19:19,033 --> 00:19:21,661
I think you need one of these.

268
00:19:21,744 --> 00:19:23,996
Thank you. That's very kind of you.

269
00:19:25,164 --> 00:19:30,628
-Do you know that man?
-No. He's a friend of my daughter's.

270
00:19:32,129 --> 00:19:35,591
Perhaps she should choose
her friends more carefully.

271
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:43,265
Where are they?

272
00:19:43,391 --> 00:19:45,518
The fluctuating DNA
will give off an energy signature.

273
00:19:45,601 --> 00:19:47,687
I might be able to pick it up.

274
00:19:49,271 --> 00:19:51,565
-Got him.
-Where?

275
00:19:51,649 --> 00:19:54,151
But this is the top floor. The roof!

276
00:19:55,111 --> 00:19:58,364
That clock tower is beautiful
all it up like that.

277
00:19:58,447 --> 00:20:03,119
It's Southwark Cathedral.
One of the oldest churches in London.

278
00:20:03,994 --> 00:20:07,123
Been around even longer than I have.

279
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:09,834
But you're looking pretty good
for your age.

280
00:20:09,917 --> 00:20:11,669
Thank you.

281
00:20:12,962 --> 00:20:14,964
-Can I?
-Of course.

282
00:20:23,681 --> 00:20:27,893
-I still can't take it in.
-I'm still adjusting myself.

283
00:20:29,395 --> 00:20:31,522
I've been working toward it
for so many years,

284
00:20:31,647 --> 00:20:34,859
it's hard to believe
the moment's finally arrived.

285
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:37,194
And is it like you expected?

286
00:20:38,654 --> 00:20:42,116
I find that nothing's
ever exactly like you expect.

287
00:20:42,783 --> 00:20:45,661
There's always something
to surprise you.

288
00:20:47,329 --> 00:20:51,083
Between the idea and the reality,
between the motion and the act...

289
00:20:51,167 --> 00:20:53,043
Falls the shadow.

290
00:20:54,336 --> 00:20:57,590
So, the mysterious Doctor
knows his Eliot.

291
00:20:57,673 --> 00:20:59,091
I'm impressed.

292
00:20:59,175 --> 00:21:02,011
-Martha, what are you doing here?
-Tish, get away from him.

293
00:21:02,136 --> 00:21:03,721
What? Don't tell me what to do.

294
00:21:03,804 --> 00:21:05,765
I wouldn't have thought
you had time for poetry, Lazarus.

295
00:21:05,848 --> 00:21:08,642
What with you being so busy defying
the laws of nature and everything.

296
00:21:08,726 --> 00:21:10,311
You're right, Doctor.

297
00:21:10,394 --> 00:21:13,731
One lifetime's been too short for me
to do everything I'd like.

298
00:21:13,814 --> 00:21:17,902
How much more I'll get done
in two or three or four.

299
00:21:18,194 --> 00:21:20,279
It doesn't work like that.

300
00:21:20,362 --> 00:21:24,325
Some people live more in 20 years
than others do in 80.

301
00:21:24,408 --> 00:21:26,869
It's not the time that matters,
it's the person.

302
00:21:26,952 --> 00:21:31,123
But if it's the right person,
what a gift that would be.

303
00:21:31,207 --> 00:21:33,918
Or what a curse.

304
00:21:34,001 --> 00:21:37,171
Look at what you've done to yourself.

305
00:21:37,254 --> 00:21:39,298
Who are you to judge me?

306
00:21:39,381 --> 00:21:41,050
Over here, Tish.

307
00:21:41,217 --> 00:21:42,968
You have to spoil everything, don't you?

308
00:21:43,052 --> 00:21:45,429
Every time I find someone nice,
you have to try and find fault.

309
00:21:45,513 --> 00:21:46,931
Tish, he's a monster!

310
00:21:47,014 --> 00:21:49,809
I know the age thing's a bit freaky,
but it works for Catherine Zeta-Jones.

311
00:21:49,892 --> 00:21:51,602
(LAZARUS GASPING)

312
00:21:51,727 --> 00:21:53,896
(FLESH TEARING)

313
00:22:02,154 --> 00:22:04,198
What is that?

314
00:22:05,783 --> 00:22:07,409
DOCTOR: Run!

315
00:22:07,493 --> 00:22:09,245
(LAZARUS GROWLING)

316
00:22:15,835 --> 00:22:18,128
-Are you okay?
-I was gonna snog him!

317
00:22:22,508 --> 00:22:23,676
WOMAN ON PA: Security One.

318
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:25,302
(ALARM BLARING)

319
00:22:25,386 --> 00:22:29,348
Security One. Security One.

320
00:22:29,682 --> 00:22:31,892
-What's happening?
-An intrusion.

321
00:22:31,976 --> 00:22:34,770
It triggers a security lockdown.
Kills most of the power.

322
00:22:34,895 --> 00:22:36,939
Stops the lifts, seals the exits.

323
00:22:37,022 --> 00:22:40,025
He must be breaking through that door.

324
00:22:40,109 --> 00:22:41,777
The stairs. Come on!

325
00:22:45,281 --> 00:22:47,241
(DOOR BREAKING)

326
00:22:47,324 --> 00:22:49,702
-He's inside!
-We haven't got much time!

327
00:22:52,788 --> 00:22:54,874
Tish, is there another way out of here?

328
00:22:54,957 --> 00:22:56,750
There's an exit in the corner,
but it'll be locked now.

329
00:22:56,834 --> 00:22:59,211
Martha, setting 54. Hurry.

330
00:23:00,629 --> 00:23:04,258
Listen to me!
You people are in serious danger.

331
00:23:04,341 --> 00:23:06,260
You need to get out of here right now!

332
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:09,096
Don't be ridiculous. The biggest danger
here is choking on an olive.

333
00:23:09,179 --> 00:23:10,681
(GLASS SHATTERING)

334
00:23:12,099 --> 00:23:14,101
(ROARING)

335
00:23:31,994 --> 00:23:34,079
LEO: Mum, get back!

336
00:23:34,163 --> 00:23:35,456
Leo!

337
00:23:36,582 --> 00:23:40,461
Over here. This way!
Everyone down the stairs now. Hurry!

338
00:23:47,968 --> 00:23:49,803
No! Get away from her!

339
00:23:57,186 --> 00:23:59,438
Leo? Leo?

340
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:09,114
Lazarus! Leave them alone.

341
00:24:10,407 --> 00:24:13,077
-Martha.
-Come on, stay with me.

342
00:24:13,160 --> 00:24:16,497
What's the point? You can't control it.
The mutation's too strong.

343
00:24:16,580 --> 00:24:20,417
Killing those people won't help you.
You're a fool.

344
00:24:21,377 --> 00:24:24,838
A vain old man
who thought he could defy nature.

345
00:24:24,922 --> 00:24:28,133
Only nature got her own back,
didn't she?

346
00:24:28,258 --> 00:24:30,219
You're a joke, Lazarus!

347
00:24:31,387 --> 00:24:34,515
A footnote in the history of failure!

348
00:24:34,598 --> 00:24:36,684
(ROARING)

349
00:24:47,403 --> 00:24:49,530
-What's the Doctor doing?
-He's trying to buy us some time.

350
00:24:49,613 --> 00:24:52,950
Let's not waste it. Leo, look at me.
Focus on me. Let's see your eyes.

351
00:24:53,033 --> 00:24:57,037
Okay, he's got concussion.
Mum, you'll need to help him downstairs.

352
00:24:58,497 --> 00:25:02,459
This'll keep the swelling down.
Go, I'll be right behind you.

353
00:25:03,877 --> 00:25:05,963
Tish, move. We need to get out of here.

354
00:25:34,992 --> 00:25:39,329
LAZARUS: It's no good, Doctor.
You can't stop me.

355
00:25:39,413 --> 00:25:40,914
Is that the same arrogance you had

356
00:25:40,998 --> 00:25:43,250
when you swore that nothing
had gone wrong with your device?

357
00:25:43,333 --> 00:25:47,838
The arrogance is yours.
You can't stand in the way of progress.

358
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:50,966
You call feeding on
innocent people progress?

359
00:25:51,800 --> 00:25:53,635
You're delusional!

360
00:25:53,761 --> 00:25:57,222
It is a necessary sacrifice.

361
00:25:57,306 --> 00:25:59,141
That's not your decision to make.

362
00:26:02,728 --> 00:26:04,646
TISH: We can't get out! We're trapped!

363
00:26:04,772 --> 00:26:07,399
There must be an override switch.
Where's the security desk? Tish!

364
00:26:07,483 --> 00:26:09,234
There.

365
00:26:19,036 --> 00:26:20,704
(DOOR OPENING)

366
00:26:29,505 --> 00:26:31,799
LAZARUS: Peek-a-boo.

367
00:26:34,009 --> 00:26:36,011
Oh. Hello.

368
00:26:40,849 --> 00:26:43,936
-I've got to go back.
-You can't.

369
00:26:44,019 --> 00:26:46,188
You saw what that thing did.
it'll kill you.

370
00:26:46,313 --> 00:26:48,482
I don't care. I have to go.

371
00:26:49,191 --> 00:26:51,610
It's that Doctor, isn't it?

372
00:26:51,693 --> 00:26:54,446
That's what's happened to you.
That's why you've changed.

373
00:26:54,530 --> 00:26:56,782
He was biding us time, Martha.

374
00:26:56,865 --> 00:27:00,369
-Time for you to get out, too.
-I'm not leaving him.

375
00:27:02,538 --> 00:27:03,914
Martha!

376
00:27:21,557 --> 00:27:23,350
(BANGING)

377
00:27:39,533 --> 00:27:41,118
(DOOR BREAKING)

378
00:27:41,243 --> 00:27:42,995
(GLASS SHATTERING)

379
00:27:43,078 --> 00:27:48,250
More hide and seek, Doctor?
How disappointing.

380
00:27:53,046 --> 00:27:57,426
-Why don't you come out and face me?
-Have you looked in the mirror lately?

381
00:28:00,012 --> 00:28:02,264
Why would I want to face that, hmm?

382
00:28:17,779 --> 00:28:19,948
-What are you doing here?
-I'm returning this.

383
00:28:20,032 --> 00:28:21,533
-I thought you might need it.
-How did you...

384
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:23,202
I heard the explosion.
I guessed it was you.

385
00:28:23,285 --> 00:28:25,704
-I blasted Lazarus.
-Did you kill him?

386
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:28,373
More sort of annoyed him, I'd say.

387
00:28:29,499 --> 00:28:30,876
She'll be all right.

388
00:28:32,211 --> 00:28:34,796
The Doctor and her,
they'll look out for each other.

389
00:28:34,922 --> 00:28:38,634
She turned her back on us,
went in there with that thing.

390
00:28:39,801 --> 00:28:42,804
-For him.
-He must be some guy.

391
00:28:44,014 --> 00:28:47,392
-Maybe she loves him.
-She just met him.

392
00:28:47,476 --> 00:28:49,770
Is your daughter still in there
with the Doctor?

393
00:28:49,853 --> 00:28:51,521
Do you know him?

394
00:28:53,148 --> 00:28:54,900
He's dangerous.

395
00:28:54,983 --> 00:28:58,487
-There are things you should know.
-What things?

396
00:29:00,030 --> 00:29:02,032
(WHISPERING)

397
00:29:06,119 --> 00:29:08,163
What now?
We've just gone round in a circle.

398
00:29:08,330 --> 00:29:10,832
We can't lead him outside.
Come on, get in.

399
00:29:13,502 --> 00:29:16,755
-Are we hiding?
-No, he knows we're here.

400
00:29:16,838 --> 00:29:19,091
But this is his masterpiece.

401
00:29:19,174 --> 00:29:21,927
I'm betting he won't destroy it,
not even to get at us.

402
00:29:22,010 --> 00:29:26,848
-But we're trapped.
-Well, yeah, that is a slight problem.

403
00:29:26,974 --> 00:29:30,269
-You mean you don't have a plan?
-Yes. The plan was to get inside here.

404
00:29:30,352 --> 00:29:32,896
-Then what?
-Well,

405
00:29:32,980 --> 00:29:35,524
then I'd come up with another plan.

406
00:29:35,607 --> 00:29:37,609
In your own time, then.

407
00:29:42,781 --> 00:29:45,492
-Hey!
-Sorry, sorry, sorry.

408
00:29:45,575 --> 00:29:48,537
-Here we are.
-What are you going to do with that?

409
00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:49,997
Improvise.

410
00:29:55,877 --> 00:29:59,464
I still don't understand
where that thing came from. Is it alien?

411
00:29:59,548 --> 00:30:01,466
No. For once,
it's strictly human in origin.

412
00:30:01,550 --> 00:30:03,385
Human? How can it be human?

413
00:30:03,510 --> 00:30:05,512
Probably from dormant genes
in Lazarus' DNA.

414
00:30:05,595 --> 00:30:07,723
The energy field in this thing
must've reactivated them.

415
00:30:07,806 --> 00:30:10,559
-Looks like they're becoming dominant.
-So it's a throwback.

416
00:30:10,642 --> 00:30:13,478
Some option that evolution rejected
for you millions of years ago.

417
00:30:13,603 --> 00:30:16,231
But the potential is still there,
locked away in your genes,

418
00:30:16,315 --> 00:30:19,026
forgotten about until Lazarus
unlocked it by mistake.

419
00:30:19,109 --> 00:30:22,446
-It's like Pandora"s box.
-Exactly. Nice shoes, by the way.

420
00:30:29,578 --> 00:30:31,079
Doctor, what's happening?

421
00:30:31,204 --> 00:30:32,789
Sounds like he's switched
the machine on.

422
00:30:32,914 --> 00:30:34,833
-That's not good, is it?
-I was hoping

423
00:30:34,916 --> 00:30:38,128
it was going to take him
a little bit longer to work that out.

424
00:30:39,921 --> 00:30:42,841
-I don't want to hurry you, but...
-I know. Nearly done.

425
00:30:42,966 --> 00:30:44,009
What are you doing?

426
00:30:44,092 --> 00:30:46,428
Trying to set the capsule to
reflect energy rather than receive it.

427
00:30:46,511 --> 00:30:47,554
Will that kill him?

428
00:30:47,637 --> 00:30:49,556
When he transforms,
he's three times the size,

429
00:30:49,639 --> 00:30:52,851
cellular triplication,
so he's spreading himself thin.

430
00:30:54,061 --> 00:30:56,938
-We're going to end up like him!
-Just one more.

431
00:31:08,867 --> 00:31:11,203
I thought we were going to go
through the blender then.

432
00:31:11,286 --> 00:31:14,790
It really shouldn't take that long
just to reverse the polarity.

433
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:17,292
I must be a bit out of practice.

434
00:31:24,132 --> 00:31:28,720
Oh, God. He seems so human again.

435
00:31:30,347 --> 00:31:33,642
-It's kind of pitiful.
-Eliot saw that, too.

436
00:31:35,060 --> 00:31:37,687
This is the way the world ends.

437
00:31:37,771 --> 00:31:40,148
Not with a bang but a whimper.

438
00:32:04,381 --> 00:32:07,092
She's here. Oh, she's all right.

439
00:32:07,175 --> 00:32:10,137
Oh, Mrs Jones.
We still haven't finished our chat.

440
00:32:11,179 --> 00:32:13,432
Keep away from my daughter.

441
00:32:13,515 --> 00:32:16,601
-Mum, what are you doing?
-Always the mothers. Every time.

442
00:32:16,685 --> 00:32:21,356
-He is dangerous. I've been told things.
-What are you talking about?

443
00:32:21,481 --> 00:32:25,360
Look around you.
Nothing but death and destruction.

444
00:32:25,444 --> 00:32:28,029
This isn't his fault.
He saved us. All of us.

445
00:32:28,113 --> 00:32:30,907
It was Tish who invited everyone
to this thing in the first place

446
00:32:31,032 --> 00:32:33,702
so I'd say, technically, it's her fault.

447
00:32:33,785 --> 00:32:35,829
(CRASHING)

448
00:32:41,126 --> 00:32:42,961
Leave him.

449
00:32:48,008 --> 00:32:50,635
-Martha?
-Not you, too.

450
00:32:52,596 --> 00:32:54,181
Sorry.

451
00:32:58,977 --> 00:33:02,147
Lazarus, back from the dead.
Should've known really.

452
00:33:02,272 --> 00:33:04,274
Where's he gone?

453
00:33:07,527 --> 00:33:11,406
-That way. The church.
-Cathedral.

454
00:33:12,199 --> 00:33:14,910
It's Southwark Cathedral. He told me.

455
00:33:31,092 --> 00:33:33,428
Do you think he's in here?

456
00:33:33,512 --> 00:33:36,431
Where would you go
if you were looking for sanctuary?

457
00:34:09,047 --> 00:34:10,840
I came here before.

458
00:34:11,883 --> 00:34:14,344
A lifetime ago.

459
00:34:14,469 --> 00:34:19,724
I thought I was going to die then.
In fact, I was sure of it.

460
00:34:20,725 --> 00:34:23,895
I sat here, just a child.

461
00:34:25,730 --> 00:34:28,942
The sound of planes and bombs outside.

462
00:34:29,025 --> 00:34:30,860
The Blitz.

463
00:34:32,112 --> 00:34:34,864
-You've read about it.
-I was there.

464
00:34:37,117 --> 00:34:38,827
You're too young.

465
00:34:39,911 --> 00:34:41,329
So are you.

466
00:34:50,380 --> 00:34:54,759
In the morning the fires had died,
but I was still alive.

467
00:34:56,636 --> 00:34:59,431
I swore I'd never face death
like that again.

468
00:35:00,932 --> 00:35:03,435
So defenceless.

469
00:35:05,061 --> 00:35:09,024
I would arm myself.
Fight back. Defeat it.

470
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:11,026
That's what you were trying to do today?

471
00:35:11,109 --> 00:35:12,986
That's what I did today.

472
00:35:13,069 --> 00:35:16,865
-What about the other people who died?
-They were nothing.

473
00:35:17,616 --> 00:35:20,952
-I changed the course of history.
-Any of them might've done, too.

474
00:35:21,036 --> 00:35:24,205
You think history's only made
with equations?

475
00:35:25,707 --> 00:35:29,794
Facing death is part of being human.
You can't change that.

476
00:35:29,878 --> 00:35:35,050
No, Doctor.
Avoiding death, that's being human.

477
00:35:35,717 --> 00:35:40,347
It's our strongest impulse, to cling
to life with every fibre of being.

478
00:35:40,430 --> 00:35:44,059
I'm only doing what everyone
before me has tried to do.

479
00:35:44,559 --> 00:35:47,437
I've simply been more successful.

480
00:35:49,147 --> 00:35:51,358
Look at yourself. You're mutating.

481
00:35:51,441 --> 00:35:53,985
You've no control over it.
You call that a success?

482
00:35:54,110 --> 00:35:55,904
I call it progress.

483
00:36:00,408 --> 00:36:02,494
I'm more now than I was.

484
00:36:04,746 --> 00:36:07,165
More than just an ordinary human.

485
00:36:07,248 --> 00:36:09,918
There's no such thing
as an ordinary human.

486
00:36:11,503 --> 00:36:14,339
-He's going to change again any minute.
-I know.

487
00:36:14,464 --> 00:36:16,549
If I could get him up
into the bell tower somehow,

488
00:36:16,633 --> 00:36:19,552
-I've an idea that might work.
-Up there?

489
00:36:27,352 --> 00:36:31,648
You're so sentimental, Doctor.
Maybe you are older than you look.

490
00:36:31,731 --> 00:36:36,069
I'm old enough to know that a longer
life isn't always a better one.

491
00:36:36,945 --> 00:36:39,322
In the end, you just get tired.

492
00:36:40,573 --> 00:36:42,826
Tired of the struggle.

493
00:36:42,951 --> 00:36:45,995
Tired of losing everyone
that matters to you.

494
00:36:48,248 --> 00:36:51,584
Tired of watching everything
turn to dust.

495
00:36:53,628 --> 00:36:56,172
If you live long enough, Lazarus,

496
00:36:56,256 --> 00:36:59,676
the only certainty left
is that you'll end up alone.

497
00:37:01,136 --> 00:37:03,430
That's a price worth paying.

498
00:37:05,140 --> 00:37:06,474
Is it?

499
00:37:18,027 --> 00:37:20,572
I will feed soon.

500
00:37:20,655 --> 00:37:22,741
I'm not going to let that happen.

501
00:37:24,367 --> 00:37:28,329
-You've not been able to stop me so far.
-Leave him, Lazarus.

502
00:37:29,330 --> 00:37:31,583
He's old and bitter.

503
00:37:31,666 --> 00:37:33,835
I thought you had a taste
for fresher meat.

504
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:35,712
Martha, no.

505
00:37:36,671 --> 00:37:38,590
-What are you doing?
-Keeping you out of trouble.

506
00:37:38,673 --> 00:37:40,884
Doctor, the tower!

507
00:37:49,684 --> 00:37:51,686
Did you hear that?

508
00:37:54,522 --> 00:37:58,109
He's changed again. Keep moving.
We've got to lead him up.

509
00:37:58,193 --> 00:37:59,569
(LAZARUS GROWLING)

510
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:04,699
Where are they?

511
00:38:06,117 --> 00:38:07,243
Martha?

512
00:38:08,703 --> 00:38:09,788
Doctor!

513
00:38:09,871 --> 00:38:12,707
Take him to the top, the very top
of the bell tower, do you hear me?

514
00:38:12,791 --> 00:38:14,584
-Up to the top?
-Martha?

515
00:38:14,709 --> 00:38:17,712
-And then what?
-Martha, come on!

516
00:38:35,897 --> 00:38:38,399
Hypersonic sound waves, inspired.

517
00:38:45,073 --> 00:38:46,950
There's nowhere else to go.
We're trapped!

518
00:38:47,033 --> 00:38:48,701
This is where he said to bring him.

519
00:38:48,785 --> 00:38:51,079
Right, so we're not trapped, we're bait.

520
00:38:51,204 --> 00:38:53,540
He knows what he's doing.
We have to trust him.

521
00:38:53,665 --> 00:38:55,416
Ladies.

522
00:39:00,088 --> 00:39:02,423
Stay behind me.

523
00:39:02,507 --> 00:39:04,926
If he takes me, make a run for it.
Head back down the stairs.

524
00:39:05,051 --> 00:39:06,594
-You should have enough time.
-But...

525
00:39:06,719 --> 00:39:08,638
Just do it, Tish!

526
00:39:11,182 --> 00:39:12,767
(MARTHA AND TISH SCREAM)

527
00:39:12,892 --> 00:39:15,436
I hope there's a good acoustic in here.

528
00:39:30,034 --> 00:39:31,077
Martha!

529
00:39:31,160 --> 00:39:33,830
(SCREAMING)

530
00:39:33,955 --> 00:39:35,290
Hold on!

531
00:39:37,250 --> 00:39:39,127
Get away from her!

532
00:39:47,802 --> 00:39:49,596
We need to turn this up to 11.

533
00:40:16,831 --> 00:40:18,917
I've got you! Hold on.

534
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:20,627
Martha!

535
00:40:29,594 --> 00:40:33,056
I'm okay. We're both okay!

536
00:40:38,394 --> 00:40:39,604
Thanks.

537
00:40:39,687 --> 00:40:42,106
It's your Doctor you should be thanking.

538
00:40:42,190 --> 00:40:45,652
-I told you he'd think of something.
-He cut it a bit fine though, didn't he?

539
00:40:45,777 --> 00:40:48,529
He always does. It's more fun that way.

540
00:40:49,572 --> 00:40:51,366
Who is he?

541
00:40:53,785 --> 00:40:55,286
He's...

542
00:40:57,747 --> 00:40:59,874
He's the Doctor.

543
00:41:31,656 --> 00:41:33,449
I didn't know you could play.

544
00:41:33,574 --> 00:41:35,660
Well, you know,
if you hang around with Beethoven,

545
00:41:35,743 --> 00:41:37,495
-you're bound to pick a few things up.
-Mmm.

546
00:41:37,578 --> 00:41:41,582
-Especially about playing loud.
-Sorry?

547
00:41:49,215 --> 00:41:51,300
Something else
that just kind of escalated, then.

548
00:41:51,426 --> 00:41:53,136
I can see a pattern developing.

549
00:41:53,261 --> 00:41:56,305
You should take more care
in the future. And the past.

550
00:41:56,431 --> 00:41:59,517
And whatever other time period
you find yourself in.

551
00:41:59,600 --> 00:42:02,437
-It's been fun, though, hasn't it?
-Yes!

552
00:42:02,562 --> 00:42:05,273
So what do you say? One more trip?

553
00:42:09,736 --> 00:42:11,863
No.

554
00:42:11,946 --> 00:42:13,114
Sorry.

555
00:42:13,197 --> 00:42:14,824
What do you mean?
I thought you liked it.

556
00:42:14,907 --> 00:42:17,827
I do, but I can't go on like this.
"One more trip." It's not fair.

557
00:42:17,952 --> 00:42:19,287
What are you talking about?

558
00:42:19,412 --> 00:42:23,291
I don't want to be a passenger any more,
someone that you take along for a treat.

559
00:42:23,374 --> 00:42:26,461
That's how you still see me.
I'd rather stay here.

560
00:42:27,670 --> 00:42:30,298
Okay, then, if that's what you want.

561
00:42:33,468 --> 00:42:36,554
Right. Well, we've already
said goodbye once today.

562
00:42:36,637 --> 00:42:39,182
It's probably best if you just go.

563
00:42:43,561 --> 00:42:46,355
-What is it?
-Well, I said okay.

564
00:42:46,481 --> 00:42:48,941
-Sorry?
-Okay.

565
00:42:50,276 --> 00:42:52,653
Oh, thank you! Thank you!

566
00:42:55,031 --> 00:42:58,826
Well, you were never really
just a passenger, were you?

567
00:43:02,413 --> 00:43:04,373
(PHONE RINGING)

568
00:43:04,499 --> 00:43:06,501
Hi, I'm out. Leave a message.

569
00:43:06,584 --> 00:43:10,088
Martha, it's your mother.
Please phone me back.

570
00:43:10,171 --> 00:43:13,132
I'm begging you.
I know who this Doctor really is.

571
00:43:13,216 --> 00:43:16,636
I know he's dangerous.
You're going to get yourself killed.

572
00:43:16,719 --> 00:43:21,099
Please trust me. This information comes
from Harold Saxon himself.

573
00:43:21,182 --> 00:43:23,184
You're not safe.

574
00:43:28,439 --> 00:43:30,566
Distress signal. Locking on.

575
00:43:30,650 --> 00:43:33,194
Now that is hot.
If you can't stand the heat...

576
00:43:33,945 --> 00:43:35,863
-The ship's gone mad.
-Who are you?

577
00:43:35,988 --> 00:43:37,031
I'm the Doctor.

578
00:43:37,115 --> 00:43:38,574
Mum, it's me, it's Martha.

579
00:43:38,699 --> 00:43:40,785
Get out of there!

580
00:43:40,868 --> 00:43:42,870
Burn with me.

581
00:43:44,622 --> 00:43:46,499
-I can't stop it!
-That's enough!

582
00:43:47,959 --> 00:43:49,752
Go on, my son.

583
00:43:49,877 --> 00:43:52,547
-That is brilliant.
-I know.

584
00:43:52,755 --> 00:43:55,633
-I'll save you.
-It's your fault.

585
00:43:55,716 --> 00:43:57,885
-What are you?
-Doctor!

586
00:43:58,010 --> 00:43:59,178
We're stuck here.

